<item>
            <title>[JDK-8304815] Use NMT for more precise hs_err location printing</title>
                <link>https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8304815</link>
                <project id="10100" key="JDK">JDK</project>
                    <description>Back in 2022 Zhengyu Gu had the very nice idea of using NMT mapping info for smartening up pp in gdb: &lt;a href=&quot;https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8280289&quot; title=&quot;Enhance debug pp() command with NMT info&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;JDK-8280289&quot;&gt;&lt;strike&gt;JDK-8280289&lt;/strike&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
The same idea could be applied to hs_err file location printing. NMT has information about all its mappings and can tell us where it thinks a given unknown pointer points into.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
This could be even more useful if the &amp;quot;find malloc block&amp;quot; part of that functionality would be smarter. As it is now, it only works if the pointer in question points to the start of a user-allocated area. Would be nice if the code could (carefully) search for the next valid-looking malloc header instead.</description>
